    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-12-12T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-12-12T15:00:00-05:00" n="676"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d676">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">560.AL/10–1945: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-12-12T15:00:00-05:00"
                            >December 12, 1945—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2505. Reurtel no. 3597, Oct 19. Dept aware many of the matters to be discussed in
                    proposed negotiations are primarily applicable to countries with economies based
                    on private enterprise. However, you will note from enclosure to Depts circular
                    instruction, Nov 14, that US trade proposals do deal with question of rules for
                    state trading which directly affect U.S.S.R. U.S.S.R., having complete monopoly
                    of foreign trade, would be asked to agree to purchase foreign goods <pb
                        facs="1361" n="1349" xml:id="pg_1349"/> up to minimum value in return for
                    tariff and other trade barrier reductions on part of other countries.</p>
                <p>In return for most-favored-nation treatment, which would be offered to U.S.S.R.,
                    U.S.S.R. would be asked to enter into commitment not to discriminate against
                    commerce of other countries and to make all external purchases and sales solely
                    on basis of commercial considerations.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
